label("$60^\circ$",(1,sqrt(3)),2SE+E);
label("$30^\circ$",(2,0),5NNW+4N);
label("6",(1.5,sqrt(3)),N);
label("$6\sqrt{3}$",(2,sqrt(3)/2),E);
label("12",(1.5,sqrt(3)/2),SW);
label("12",(1,0),S);
[/asy]

Using the quadratic formula $x = \frac{ - b \pm \sqrt {b^2 - 4ac} }{2a}$, we can find the roots of the quadratic. We find that $x = \frac{-5 \pm \sqrt{25-4c}}{2}$. Thus, setting our two expressions for $x$ equal to each other, we find that  \begin{align*}
\frac{-5 \pm \sqrt{25-4c}}{2} &= \frac{-5 \pm \sqrt{c}}{2} \quad \Rightarrow \\
25 - 4c &= c \quad \Rightarrow \\
c &= \boxed{5}.
\end{align*}

Since $\left(\frac{1}{4}, -6\right)$ lies on the line, we plug $x = \frac{1}{4}$ and $y = -6$ into the equation to get  \begin{align*}
-\frac{1}{2} - \frac{k}{2} &= 5(-6)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -1-k = -60\\
\Rightarrow\qquad k=\boxed{59}.
\end{align*}

